==Development and preparation==
{{Main|2012 Summer Olympic development}}
As with the Olympics, the 2012 Summer Paralympics were overseen by [[LOCOG]] and the [[Olympic Delivery Authority]] (ODA). LOCOG was responsible for overseeing the staging of the games, while the ODA dealt with infrastructure and venues.<ref>{{Citation |author=London 2012|authorlink=LOCOG|year=2005|title=LOCOG Formally Established|url=http://www.olympic.org/content/news/media-resources/manual-news/1999-2009/2005/10/07/london-2012-locog-formally-established/|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|author=Olympic Delivery Authority|authorlink=Olympic Delivery Authority |year=2007 |title=Annual Report and Accounts 2006-2007|publisher=Olympic Delivery Authority|publication-place= London|page=10|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/250791/0741.pdf|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>

The [[Government Olympic Executive]] (GOE) within the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] (DCMS) was the lead Government body for co-ordinating the London 2012 Olympics and Paralympics. The GOE reported through the DCMS Permanent Secretary to the Minister for Sports and the Olympics [[Hugh Robertson (politician)|Hugh Robertson]]. It focused on oversight of the Games, cross-programme management and the [[London 2012 Olympic Legacy]].<ref>{{Citation|author=Government Olympic Executive|authorlink=Government Olympic Executive|year=2011|title=London 2012 Olympic and Paralympic Games Annual Report February 2011|publisher=Department for Culture, Media and Sport|publication-place= London|page=2|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/77633/DCMS_GOE_annual_report_february_2011.pdf|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>

===Venues and infrastructure===
[[File:ParalympicCyclingatBrandsHatch.jpg|thumb|200px|right|The [[Brands Hatch]] circuit hosted [[road cycling]] during the Paralympics.]]
{{Further|Venues of the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics}}
The 2012 Summer Paralympics used many of the same venues as the 2012 Summer Olympics, along with several new locations such as [[Eton Manor]] for wheelchair tennis and [[Brands Hatch]] for road cycling.<ref name=guardian-paraprep/> London's purpose-built Olympic venues and facilities, including the Olympic Village itself, were designed to be accessible as possible so they could easily accommodate the Paralympics. Some venues also contained additional accessible seating areas during the Paralympics.<ref name=guardian-paraprep>{{cite news|title=London 2012: let the Paralympics preparations begin|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/13/london-2012-paralympic-preparations-begin?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=18 August 2012|first=Alexandra|last=Topping|date=13 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=paralympic-twists>{{cite news|last=Gibson|first=Owen|title=Paralympics reignite the Olympic buzz but with added twists|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/30/london-paralympics-olympics-differences-similiarities?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=31 August 2012|location=London|date=30 August 2012}}</ref>

===Public transport===
{{See also|2012 Summer Olympics#Public transport}}
[[Transport for London]] operated the Paralympic Route Network (a downsized version of the Olympic Route Network operated during the Summer Olympics) to facilitate road traffic between venues and facilities. The network provided {{convert|8.7|mi|abbr=off}} of lanes specifically reserved for Paralympic athletes and officials.<ref name=lm-prn>{{cite web|title=London sets out road plans for Paralympics|url=http://www.logisticsmanager.com/Articles/19021/London+sets+out+road+plans+for+Paralympics.html|publisher=Logistics Manager|accessdate=15 August 2012}}</ref> TfL continued to operate its ''Get Ahead of the Games'' website during the Paralympics, which provided updates and advice for commuters during the Games.<ref name=les-cycling>{{cite news |title=The Olympic commute... Get ahead of the Games by bike |url= http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/london-life/the-olympic-commute-get-ahead-of-the-games-by-bike-7978591.html | work = [[London Evening Standard]] |date=26 July 2012 |author=Gardner, Jasmine |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> Prior to the Games, concerns were raised by TfL commissioner [[Peter Hendy]] that London's transportation system might not be able to handle the Paralympics adequately. He feared that the end of the school summer holiday (which fell during the Games) would result in increased traffic, and that commuters might not heed traffic warnings or change their travel behaviour as they had during the Olympics.<ref name=guardian-transport>{{cite news|title=Transport fears as Paralympic ticket sales surge|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/uk/2012/aug/12/paralympic-games-london-transport-fears?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=13 August 2012|location=London|first1=Gwyn|last1=Topham|first2=Alexandra|last2=Topping|date=12 August 2012}}</ref>

[[Sevenoaks railway station]] was designated as the preferred station for spectators travelling to watch the cycling at [[Brands Hatch]]. Organisers chose Sevenoaks over the closer [[Swanley railway station]] because of its "existing step-free access and excellent transport links", and because Swanley did not yet have a [[wheelchair lift]]. Whilst organisers did not believe that Swanley would be able to have wheelchair lifts installed by the start of the Paralympics, the station finished their installation by early August 2012.<ref name=bbc-swanley-lifts>{{cite news|title=New station lifts open in time for Paralympics|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-kent-19258777|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=15 August 2012|date=14 August 2012}}</ref>

===Lead-up and promotion===
[[File:London 2012 countdown clock (1).jpg|thumb|A digital clock in [[Trafalgar Square]], counting down to the opening ceremony of the 2012 Summer Paralympics]]

====Handover ceremony====
The formal handover occurred during the closing ceremony of the [[2008 Summer Paralympics]] in Beijing, when [[Mayor of London]] [[Boris Johnson]] received the [[Paralympic flag#Flag|Paralympic Flag]] from Mayor of Beijing [[Guo Jinlong]]. This was followed by a cultural presentation by Britain, which was similar to its presentation during the [[2008 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|Olympics' closing ceremony]]. It featured urban dance group ZooNation, the [[Royal Ballet]], and [[Candoco]], a [[physically integrated dance]] group, all dressed as London commuters and waiting for a bus by a zebra crossing. A double-decker bus drove around the stadium, guided by [[Ade Adepitan]], to music composed by [[Philip Sheppard (musician)|Philip Sheppard]]. The top of the bus was open and folded down to show a privet hedge featuring London landmarks such as [[Tower Bridge]], [[30 St Mary Axe|The Gherkin]] and the [[London Eye]]. [[Cherisse Osei]], drummer for [[Mika (singer)|Mika]], and Sam Hegedus then performed, before the top of the bus folded up into its original form, sporting multi-coloured Paralympic livery.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://www.london2012.com/documents/press-kits/paralympic-handover-media-guide.pdf |title=Media guide to the London 2012 Paralympic Games Handover segment, Closing Ceremony, Beijing 2008 Games. |publisher=London 2012 |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=20 August 2011}}</ref> Both the Paralympic and Olympic flags were formally raised outside of London's [[City Hall (London)|City Hall]] on 26 September 2008. British Paralympians [[Helene Raynsford]] and [[Chris Holmes (swimmer)|Chris Holmes]] raised the Paralympic flag.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/mayor/videos/flag-raising.jsp |title=Mayor of London&nbsp;<U+2014> Video clips: Olympic and Paralympic flags raised at City Hall |publisher=Legacy.london.gov.uk |date=26 September 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://legacy.london.gov.uk/view_press_release.jsp?releaseid=18998 |title=1948 Olympians and 2012 hopefuls join Beijing heroes as Olympic and Paralympic flags raised at City Hall |publisher=Legacy.london.gov.uk |date=26 September 2008 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref>

====Paralympic Day and Super Saturday====

On 8 September 2011 [[Trafalgar Square]] staged ''International Paralympic Day'', hosted by [[Rick Edwards]], [[Ade Adepitan]] and [[Iwan Thomas]], to coincide with a visit to London by representatives of the IPC. The event celebrated the Paralympic Games, showcasing and demonstrating the 20 sports that would feature during the Games (with some sessions also made inclusive to people with hearing disabilities). It also featured appearances by Paralympic athletes [[Oscar Pistorius]] (of whom a bronze statue by [[Ben Dearnley]] was unveiled as well), [[Ellie Simmonds]] and [[Sascha Kindred]]. British Prime Minister [[David Cameron]] and London's mayor Boris Johnson also appeared.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/london-2012-host-international-paralympic-day-september-2011|title=London 2012 to Host International Paralympic Day in September 2011|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14819063 | publisher=BBC News | title=London 2012: David Cameron visits Paralympic Day | date=8 September 2011}}</ref> Two days later on 10 September, supermarket chain [[Sainsbury's]] and [[Channel 4]] presented ''Sainsbury's Super Saturday'', a family event at [[Clapham Common]]. The event featured showcases of Paralympic sports, and a concert featuring pop music acts including [[Nicola Roberts]], [[Olly Murs]], [[The Wanted]], [[Will Young]], [[Pixie Lott]], [[Dappy]], [[Sugababes]], [[The Saturdays]], [[Chipmunk (rapper)|Chipmunk]] and [[Taio Cruz]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://j-sainsbury.co.uk/media/events/2011/20110910-sainsburys-super-saturday/|title=Sainsbury's Super Saturday|publisher=J Sainsbury plc|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/paralympics/summer-paralympics/2012/109672-sainsburys-super-saturday-is-a-hit-as-pop-stars-help-promote-london-2012-paralympics|title=Sainsbury<U+2019>s Super Saturday is a hit as pop stars help promote London 2012 Paralympics|publisher=Inside the Games|author= Tom Degun|date=10 September 2011 |accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>

====Channel 4 promotional campaign {{anchor|Channel 4 television advert}}====
[[Channel 4]], the host broadcaster of the 2012 Summer Paralympics in the United Kingdom, promoted its coverage of the Games with a multi-platform advertising campaign that included television adverts, online content, and [[billboard advertising]], some of which carrying the tagline "Thanks for [[2012 Summer Olympics|the warm-up]]." Overall, Channel 4's campaign aimed to change the public's view of the Paralympics, encouraging viewers to see the Games as an "event in its own right" rather than as an afterthought to the Olympics.<ref name=time-londonpromotion>{{cite news|title=After the 2012 London Olympics, Will Sponsors Embrace the Paralympics?|url=http://olympics.time.com/2012/09/07/after-london-2012-will-sponsors-and-media-finally-embrace-the-paralympics/|work=Time|accessdate=5 January 2014|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> As part of the campaign, Channel 4 produced a two-minute long trailer for its coverage entitled ''Meet the Superhumans'', which was directed by Tom Tagholm with input from the [[British Paralympic Association]]'s Tim Hollingsworth. The trailer, set to [[Public Enemy (group)|Public Enemy]]'s song "[[Harder Than You Think]]", focused on the competitive and "superhuman" aspects of Paralympic sport, while acknowledging the personal events and struggles that reflected every athlete's participation in the Games. ''Meet the Superhumans'' premiered on 17 July 2012, and aired simultaneously as a "roadblock" advert on 78 different commercial television channels in the UK (which included rival channels [[ITV1]] and [[Sky1]]).<ref name=adott-c4paralympics>{{cite web|title=Ad of the Day: Paralympic Games Forget the Olympics. This is the summer's most stunning sports commercial|url=http://www.adweek.com/news/advertising-branding/ad-day-paralympic-games-142183| work =[[Adweek]]|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=ind-c4para>{{cite news|title=Paralympics: Channel 4's superhuman effort|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/paralympics-channel-4s-superhuman-effort-7956894.html|work = [[The Independent]] |accessdate=11 August 2012|location=London|first=Simon|last=Usborne|date=19 July 2012}}</ref>

The advert was met with critical acclaim: ''[[Adweek]]'''s Tim Nudd declared it "the summer's most stunning sports commercial",<ref name=adott-c4paralympics/> while Simon Usborne of ''[[The Independent]]'' felt it was "an act of branding genius" and "a clear bid to bring the Paralympics from the sporting wings to centre stage."<ref name=ind-c4para/> The advert was seen by an estimated audience of 10 million viewers; Channel 4's marketing and communications chief Dan Brooke estimated that reaction to the advert through [[social media]] was double that of the premi<U+00E8>re of the BBC's trailer for its Olympics coverage.<ref name=adott-c4paralympics/><ref name=ind-c4para/>

''Meet the Superhumans'' won a Golden Lion award at the [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|Cannes Lions Festival]] in June 2013, losing the overall award to ''[[Dumb Ways to Die]]''. [[Bartle Bogle Hegarty|Sir John Hegarty]], the jury president said of it: "When you've got some really outstanding work it is tragic in some ways it can't get a bigger award, but there can only be one grand prix", while jury member Carlo Cavallone added "[Meet the Superhumans] is an amazing campaign, one of the golds that went through [the judging process] immediately ... Everyone felt it had the highest level of craft. It puts an issue that was really important before London 2012 to raise awareness of the Paralympics [and] they were hyper successful <U+2026> ''Dumb Ways to Die'' was a tough contender."<ref>{{cite news|title=Cannes Lions: Dumb Ways to Die scoops top award|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2013/jun/22/cannes-lions-advertising-awards|work = [[The Guardian]] |date=22 June 2013|accessdate=23 June 2013|location=London|first=Mark|last=Sweney}}</ref>

====Royal Mail stamps and gold post boxes====
{{see also|2012 Olympics gold post boxes in the United Kingdom}}
In August 2009 [[Royal Mail]] unveiled a series of 30 stamps (reflecting the 30th Olympiad) about the coming Olympic and Paralympic Games. They were released in batches of ten between 2009 and July 2011; each stamp featured an Olympic or Paralympic sport and the London 2012 logo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.royalmailgroup.com/royal-mail-launches-major-series-olympic-stamps-london-2012|title=Royal Mail launches major series of Olympic Stamps for London 2012 |publisher=Royal Mail Group |date=24 August 2009 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.insidethegames.biz/olympics/summer-olympics/2012/13670-royal-mail-releases-final-set-of-2012-olympic-stamps |title=Royal Mail releases final set of 2012 Olympic stamps &#124; London 2012 |publisher=insidethegames.biz |date=22 July 2011 |accessdate=22 September 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-14244890 | publisher=BBC News | title=Year-to-go Olympic stamps unveiled by Royal Mail | date=22 July 2011}}</ref>

Royal Mail honoured Britain's Paralympic gold medallists by painting a [[post box]] gold in each of their home towns (along with an additional post box outside the [[National Spinal Injuries Centre]] in [[Stoke Mandeville]], in honour of its role in the Games),<ref name="Pock Post">{{cite news|title=Gold Post Boxes Launched For ParalympicsGB Gold Medal Winners|url=http://www.pocklingtonpost.co.uk/community/gold-post-boxes-launched-for-paralympicsgb-gold-medal-winners-1-4876138|accessdate=10 September 2012|newspaper=Pocklington Post|date=29 August 2012}}</ref> and also featured them on commemorative stamps released throughout the Games{{emdash}}as it had done during the Olympics.<ref name=rm-stamps/><ref name=guardian-rmstamps/> Royal Mail originally planned only to release a series of six stamps with group portraits of Britain's medallists; however, the decision was met with backlash from critics, who argued that the organization was discriminating against Paralympians by not granting them the same individual recognition as their Olympian counterparts.<ref name=rm-stamps/> Olympic [[Shadow Cabinet|shadow minister]] [[Tessa Jowell]] was also critical of Royal Mail's plan, saying that the stamps were a symbolic aspect of Britain's celebration of the Olympics and that "it would be a shame if this important symbol was not offered to our Paralympian heroes as well."<ref name=guardian-rmstamps/>

Royal Mail initially defended its decision, arguing that it would have been "logistically and practically impossible" to issue individual stamps for each gold medallist, since it expected the British team to meet or exceed its performance at Beijing of 42 gold medals.<ref name=rm-stamps>{{cite news|title=Royal Mail defends decision to deny Paralympic gold medallists own stamps|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/08/royal-mail-defends-paralympic-stamps| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=12 August 2012|location=London|first=Matthew|last=Taylor|date=8 August 2012}}</ref> As a result of the criticism, Royal Mail announced on 15 August 2012 that it would release individual stamps for each British Paralympic gold medallist.<ref name=guardian-rmstamps>{{cite news|title=Royal Mail will issue stamp for every UK Paralympic gold medal winners|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/15/royal-mail-pressure-paralympics-stamps?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=16 August 2012|location=London|first=Alexandra|last=Topping|date=15 August 2012}}</ref>

====Test events====
{{main|London Prepares series}}
Several Paralympics-specific events were held during the [[London Prepares series]] of test events for the Olympic and Paralympic Games; these included the London International [[Goalball]] Tournament, and the London Disability Grand Prix<U+2014>which was also the first Paralympic event to be held at London's Olympic Stadium.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/london_2012/9397066.stm | publisher=BBC News | title=London 2012 test events unveiled | date=24 February 2011}}</ref><ref name=bbc-para-goalball>{{cite web|title=GB goalball hopeful on Paralympic place after test event|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/16033528|publisher=BBC Sport|accessdate=11 August 2012}}</ref>

===Torch relay===
{{see also|2012 Summer Paralympics torch relay}}
[[File:London 2012 Paralympic Games torch relay-7889516694.jpg|thumb|right|200px|A group of torchbearers in wheelchairs bringing the Paralympic flame through [[Canary Wharf]].]]
The Paralympic torch relay began on 22 August, when groups of [[Community integration|disabled and non-disabled]] [[Scouting and Guiding in the United Kingdom|scouts]] kindled four Paralympic flames on the highest peaks of each nation of the United Kingdom; [[Scafell Pike]] in England, [[Ben Nevis]] in Scotland, [[Slieve Donard]] in Northern Ireland, and [[Snowdon]] in Wales. On 24 August the four flames were used to light ceremonial cauldrons in London, [[Edinburgh]], [[Belfast]] and [[Cardiff]] during special "Flame Festival" events; smaller "Flame Celebration" events were also held in various communities over the [[bank holiday]] weekend.<ref name=bbc-torchrelay/><ref name=ind-relay>{{cite news|title=Mountain cauldrons will spark Paralympic torch relay|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympics/mountain-cauldrons-will-spark-paralympic-torch-relay-8050170.html|work= [[The Independent]]|accessdate=19 August 2012|location=London|first=Jerome|last=Taylor|date=15 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-relaybegin>{{cite news|title=Paralympics 2012: flames lit across Britain at the start of Paralympic torch relay celebrations|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9492379/Paralympics-2012-flames-lit-across-Britain-at-the-start-of-Paralympic-torch-relay-celebrations.html| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=23 August 2012|location=London|first=Tim|last=Williams|date=22 August 2012}}</ref>

On 28 August the four flames were united during a ceremony at [[Stoke Mandeville Stadium]].<ref name=telegraph-united>{{cite news|title=Four Paralympic flames united at Stoke Mandeville|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9504731/Four-Paralympic-flames-united-at-Stoke-Mandeville.html|work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=29 August 2012|location=London|first=Victoria|last=Ward|date=28 August 2012}}</ref> The flame then travelled a {{convert|92|mi|adj=on|abbr=off}} route to Olympic Stadium in a 24-hour relay, with 580 torchbearers working in teams of five.<ref name=bbc-torchrelay>{{cite news|title=London 2012: Scouts to spark Paralympic flame|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19265010|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=16 August 2012|date=15 August 2012}}</ref> After a two-hour weather delay, a backup flame was taken straight to the stadium as a contingency, and the relay route was modified.<ref>{{cite news|title=Paralympics 2012: Backup torch is lit after delays cause fears that flame won't make opening ceremony on time|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9507005/Paralympics-2012-Backup-torch-is-lit-after-delays-cause-fears-that-flame-wont-make-opening-ceremony-on-time.html| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=30 August 2012|location=London|date=29 August 2012}}</ref> However, as the opening ceremony's parade of nations took longer than expected, the flame was able to arrive at Olympic Stadium in time.<ref name=guardian-oczip/>

===Ticketing===
2.7 million tickets were offered in total, including event-specific tickets and those granting access solely to the Olympic Park, along with multi-event passes offered for ExCeL London and Olympic Park that were intended to allow spectators to discover a variety of Paralympic events.<ref name="paralympic-twists"/><ref name=bbc-27million/> Unlike previous Paralympics, tickets were in extremely high demand, and the ticket allocation was increased from the originally planned 2.5 million. Whilst the period during the Olympics has historically been the busiest for Paralympic sales, 1.4 million tickets were already sold before the start of the Summer Olympics, already surpassing the total number sold in Sydney.<ref name=ind-snapped>{{cite news|title=2.1m Paralympic tickets snapped up|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympics/21m-paralympic-tickets-snapped-up-8022473.html| work = [[The Independent]] |accessdate=11 August 2012|location=London|first=Helen|last=William|date=8 August 2012}}</ref> The high demand resulted in technical issues with the [[Ticketmaster]]-operated website, which led to complaints via [[social networking service]]s by users who were struggling to order.<ref name=dm-raceon>{{cite news|title=Race is on for Paralympic seats: Event set to sell out... that's if you can actually buy a ticket|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2187994/Paralympics-2012-Event-set-sell--thats-actually-buy-ticket.html| work = [[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=15 August 2012|location=London|first1=Paul|last1=Sims|first2=James|last2=Burman|date=13 August 2012}}</ref>

Organisers expected the first ever sell-out in the history of the Paralympics.<ref name=dm-paralympics23million>{{cite news|title=Final ticket rush for London 2012: Games are just 200,000 tickets away from becoming first ever sold out Paralympics|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2191254/Final-ticket-rush-London-2012-Games-just-200-000-tickets-away-sold-Paralympics.html?ito=feeds-newsxml| work = [[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=23 August 2012|first=Louise|last=Eccles|date=21 August 2012}}</ref> LOCOG's chief executive [[Paul Deighton]] remarked that "the interest in attending the Paralympics has been extraordinary from the start."<ref name=bbc-27million>{{cite news|title=Paralympics tickets raise <U+00A3>10m more than predicted|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19500185|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=6 September 2012|date=6 September 2012}}</ref> This success was attributed to the enthusiasm surrounding [[Great Britain at the 2012 Summer Olympics|Great Britain's performance during the Olympics]], fan interest in South African "Blade Runner" [[Oscar Pistorius]] (a Paralympic athlete who was the first ever double amputee to compete in the Olympics), and affordable prices.<ref name=bbc-27million/><ref name=thei-tickets>{{cite news|last=Cecil|first=Nicholas|title=Interest in 'Blade Runner' Oscar Pistorius pushes up London 2012 Paralympic ticket sales|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympics/interest-in-blade-runner-oscar-pistorius-pushes-up-london-2012-paralympic-ticket-sales-8015168.html | work = [[The Independent]] |accessdate=11 August 2012|date=7 August 2012}}</ref>

On 8 August LOCOG announced that 2.1 million tickets had been sold (600,000 in the previous month alone), breaking the record of 1.8 million set in Beijing (1.6 million tickets were also distributed by the Chinese government).<ref name=bbc-27million/> IPC president [[Philip Craven]] congratulated London for this achievement, crediting it to "the insatiable appetite the public has for top class elite sport", and noted it would be fitting for a Paralympics held in its spiritual birthplace to have filled venues.<ref name=ind-snapped/> By the opening ceremony, 2.4 million had been sold, with the remaining 100,000 sold during the Games; 10,000 were offered each day. The last 800 tickets to the Opening Ceremony were distributed to police and the military, while Mayor Boris Johnson arranged for the distribution of 1,100 to members of London's youth athletics clubs.<ref name=bbc-onsale>{{cite news|title=Paralympic tickets on sale during Games|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19399100|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=28 August 2012|date=28 August 2012}}</ref> Due to popular demand, a further 100,000 contingency tickets were released on 6 September (which included multi-event passes, and event tickets given up by sponsors and partners), along with 100,000 giving access solely to the Olympic Park.<ref name=bbc-27million/>

===Logo===
{{See also|2012 Summer Olympics#Logo}}
The 2012 Summer Paralympics used an emblem sharing a common design with that of the Summer Olympics{{emdash}}the first time this had ever been done.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/6718243.stm|title=London 2012 logo to be unveiled|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=4 June 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070613121008/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/6718243.stm| archivedate= 13 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The logo, designed by [[Wolff Olins]], was unveiled on 4 June 2007, and is a representation of the number 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/6718243.stm|title=London unveils logo of 2012 Games|publisher=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=5 July 2007| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20070613121003/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/olympics_2012/6718243.stm| archivedate= 13 June 2007 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> The Paralympic version has its own distinct colour scheme, and substitutes the [[Olympic symbols|Olympic Rings]] with the [[Paralympic symbol|Paralympic "agitos"]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.london2012.com/about-newlook-video.html|title=The new London 2012 brand|publisher=London 2012|date=4 June 2007|accessdate=4 June 2007 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20070606204757/http://www.london2012.com/about-newlook-video.html |archivedate = 6 June 2007}}</ref>

{{Wide image|2012 Summer Olympics logos.svg|600px|The Paralympics logo (far left) and the different official colour combinations of the 2012 Summer Olympics logo.}}

===Mascots===
[[File:Olympic mascots (cropped).jpg|200px|thumb|London's Paralympic and Olympic Mascots, Mandeville (left) and Wenlock (right)]]
{{Main|Wenlock and Mandeville}}
The official mascot of the 2012 Summer Paralympic Games, Mandeville, was unveiled alongside its Olympic counterpart Wenlock on 19 May 2010. As characters, they are portrayed drops of steel from a steelworks in [[Bolton]], and feature singular camera eyes{{emdash}}representing "focus" and the cameras being used to capture the Games. Mandeville is named in honour of [[Stoke Mandeville]] due to its significance in the origins of the Paralympics. Mandeville also wears a helmet emblazoned in the red, green, and blue colours of the [[Paralympic symbols#Current|Paralympic emblem]].<ref>{{cite web|title = The London 2012 mascots| publisher=London 2012| date = 19 May 2010| url = http://www.ourlondon2012.com/mascots/| accessdate =20 May 2010| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100521054503/http://www.ourlondon2012.com/mascots/| archivedate= 21 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref><ref name="BBCMascots">{{Cite news  | title = London 2012 unveils Games mascots Wenlock & Mandeville  | publisher=BBC News | date = 19 May 2010  | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/london_2012/8690467.stm  | accessdate =19 May 2010 | first=Gordon | last=Farquhar| archiveurl= http://web.archive.org/web/20100522124841/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/olympic_games/london_2012/8690467.stm| archivedate= 22 May 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Opening ceremony===
[[File:Paralympic flames.jpg|thumb|right|150px|The Paralympic cauldron.]]
{{main|2012 Summer Paralympics opening ceremony}}
The opening ceremony was held on 29 August at the Olympic Stadium. It was inspired by [[William Shakespeare]]'s play "[[The Tempest]]" and themed around the concept of "Enlightenment". It featured appearances by [[theoretical physics|theoretical physicist]] [[Stephen Hawking]], along with actors [[Ian McKellen]] and [[Nicola Miles-Wildin]] playing the roles of [[Prospero]] and [[Miranda (The Tempest)|Miranda]] from "The Tempest". The ceremony also featured a performance by British electronic music group [[Orbital (band)|Orbital]].<ref name=guardian-oczip/> The leading UK disabled theatre company [[Graeae Theatre Company|Graeae]] played their version of the polio survivor [[Ian Dury|Ian Dury's]] 1981 protest song '[[Spasticus Autisticus]]'.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://georgemckay.org/spasticus-autisticus-at-the-paralympics-opening-ceremony/|title=Spasticus Autisticus at the Paralympics opening ceremony|last1=McKay|first1=George |date=30 August 2012|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>

The final bearers of the Paralympic flame represented several generations of Paralympic athletes. Joe Townsend, a [[Royal Marines|Royal Marine]] who lost both of his legs after stepping on a [[land mine]] on duty in [[Afghanistan]] (who represented the future, as he plans to compete [[2016 Summer Paralympics|in Rio]]), delivered the flame to Olympic Stadium via a [[zipline]] from the [[ArcelorMittal Orbit]] tower. He passed the flame to long-time British [[Five-a-side football]] captain [[David Clarke (five-a-side footballer)|David Clarke]], who then passed it to the lighter of the [[2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics cauldron|Paralympic cauldron]], [[Margaret Maughan]], who was the winner of Britain's first gold medal at the [[1960 Summer Paralympics|first official Paralympics]], in Rome.<ref name=guardian-oczip>{{cite news|title=Paralympics 2012 opening ceremony: Games launched on a storm of ideas|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/30/paralympics-2012-opening-ceremony-games-launched-storm-ideas?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=30 August 2012|location=London|first=Owen|last=Gibson|date=30 August 2012}}</ref>
{{clear}}

===Closing ceremony===
{{main|2012 Summer Paralympics closing ceremony}}
The closing ceremony was held on 9 September at the Olympic Stadium. Entitled "The Festival of the Flame", the ceremony was themed around the gathering of people in celebration, and was directed by [[Kim Gavin]], who also directed the [[2012 Summer Olympics closing ceremony|closing ceremony of the Summer Olympics]] just a few weeks prior.<ref name="bbc-cc">{{cite news|title=Paralympic Games: Closing ceremony led by Coldplay|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19537677|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=10 September 2012|date=10 September 2012}}</ref> The ceremony featured sequences set to a live performance by the British rock band [[Coldplay]], who were accompanied by guest performers such as the [[British Paraorchestra]] (who accompanied the band on "[[Strawberry Swing]]", and also performed the Paralympic anthem), [[Barbadian people|Barbadian]] singer [[Rihanna]] (who performed her collaboration with Coldplay, "[[Princess of China]]", and her solo hit "[[We Found Love]]") and American rapper [[Jay-Z]] (who performed "[[Run This Town]]" with Rihanna and Coldplay, and joined in a reprise of "[[Paradise (Coldplay song)|Paradise]]"). To mark its hosting of the [[2016 Summer Paralympics]], the Paralympic flag was passed from [[Boris Johnson]], [[Mayor of London]] to [[Eduardo Paes]], [[List of mayors of Rio de Janeiro|Mayor of Rio de Janeiro]].<ref name=guardian-emotional-finale/> LOCOG chief [[Sebastian Coe]] and IPC president [[Philip Craven]] both congratulated London for its successful hosting of the Paralympics; Coe was proud that both the Olympics and Paralympics in London could be labelled "[[Country of origin|Made in Britain]]", while Sir Phillip felt that the Games were the "greatest Paralympic Games ever."<ref name=guardian-emotional-finale/> [[Ellie Simmonds]] and [[Jonnie Peacock]] shared the honour of extinguishing the Paralympic cauldron, sharing its last flame on torches to others throughout the stadium to represent its eternal spirit.<ref name=guardian-emotional-finale/><ref name=guardian-liveblog>{{cite news|title=London 2012 Paralympics closing ceremony <U+2013> as it happened|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/sep/09/london-2012-paralympics-closing-ceremony-live| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=10 September 2012|first=David|last=Batty|date=9 September 2012}}</ref>

==The Games==

===Participating nations===
London 2012 had the largest number of athletes and participating nations of any Paralympic Games.<ref name="biggest">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/it-s-official-london-2012-be-biggest-paralympic-games-ever |title=It's Official{{spaced ndash}} London 2012 to be Biggest Paralympic Games Ever |publisher=Paralympic.org |date= |accessdate=8 July 2012}}</ref> A total of 4,302 athletes from 164 countries competed in the Games. This represented an increase of 291 athletes and 18 countries from the 2008 Games, which had 4,011 athletes from 146 countries.<ref>{{cite web|date=|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/reports/participation2pdf.php?sport=all&games=2008PG&gender=|title=Participation Numbers Beijing 2008|publisher=IPC|accessdate=23 April 2014}}</ref>

Fourteen countries made their Paralympic d<U+00E9>but: [[Antigua and Barbuda]], [[Brunei]], [[Cameroon]], [[Comoros]], the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]], [[Djibouti]], [[the Gambia]], [[Guinea-Bissau]], [[Liberia]], [[Mozambique]], [[North Korea]], [[San Marino]], the [[Solomon Islands]] and the [[US Virgin Islands]].<ref name="biggest" /> [[Trinidad and Tobago]] returned to the Games for the first time since 1988.<ref>[http://www.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2012-05-16/paralympic-athletes-thrill-students "Paralympic athletes thrill students"]. ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]''. 17 May 2012.</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/trinidad-and-tobago|title=Trinidad and Tobago Paralympic Committee|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>

[[Andorra]] made its d<U+00E9>but in the [[Summer Paralympics]], having already made three appearances at the [[Winter Paralympics]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.paralympic.org/andorra|title=Andorra Paralympic Committee|publisher=International Paralympic Committee|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> [[Malawi]], which would have been making its debut at the Games, and [[Botswana]], were both due to send delegations but withdrew hours before the opening ceremony citing a lack of government funds.<ref>{{cite web|last=Degun|first=Tom|title=Botswana and Malawi pull out of London 2012 Paralympic Games|url=http://www.insideworldparasport.biz/paralympics/summer-paralympics/london-2012/10663-botswana-and-malawi-pull-out-of-london-2012-paralympic-games|publisher=inside world parasport|accessdate=29 August 2012|date=29 August 2012}}</ref>

The following [[National Paralympic Committee]]s sent delegations to compete:<ref name=participation>{{cite web|date=|url=http://www.paralympic.org/ipc_results/reports/participation2pdf.php?sport=all&games=2012PG&gender=|title=Participation Numbers London 2012|publisher=IPC|accessdate=2 November 2012}}</ref>
