*[[File:Wheelchair tennis pictogram (Paralympics).svg|17px]] [[Wheelchair tennis]]  <small>(6)</small> ({{detailslink|Wheelchair tennis at the 2012 Summer Paralympics}})
{{col-end}}

Events for athletes with [[intellectual disability|intellectual disabilities]] (ID class) returned to the Paralympics in [[Athletics at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|athletics]], [[Swimming at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|swimming]], [[Table tennis at the 2012 Summer Paralympics|table tennis]] for the first time since 2000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/disability_sport/8323369.stm |title=BBC Sport&nbsp;<U+2014> Disability Sports&nbsp;<U+2014> Intellectual disability ban ends |publisher=BBC News |date=21 November 2009 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uksportsassociation.org/news/19NewsletterJuly2010.pdf |title= President's Newsletter July 2010 |publisher= [[International Sports Federation for Persons with Intellectual Disability]] |date=July 2010|accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref> ID events had been suspended following the [[2000 Summer Paralympics]], after the [[Spain at the 2000 Summer Paralympics|Spanish]] [[Basketball ID at the 2000 Summer Paralympics|basketball]] team was [[Cheating at the Paralympic Games#Basketball controversy|stripped of their gold medals]] when it was found that only 2 of their 12 team members actually suffered from intellectual disability. The IPC would impose higher scrutiny on intellectually disabled athletes in London, and also implemented a new testing procedure to better determine eligibility.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/other_sports/disability_sport/7613787.stm |title=Paralympics set to alter entry policy |publisher=BBC News |date=13 September 2008 |accessdate=13 August 2012}}</ref>

Also beginning in 2012, [[sighted guide]]s became eligible to receive medals in certain events; sighted [[goalkeeper]]s in [[Football 5-a-side at the Summer Paralympics|5-a-side football]], along with guides and pilots in athletics and cycling were now able to receive medals for their contributions. Previously in the case of [[tandem bicycle|tandem cycling]], where a visually-impaired rider takes the rear of the bike with a sighted pilot in front, only the visually-impaired rider actually received a medal.<ref name="bbc-ablebodied">{{cite news|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-19422244 |title=Paralympics 2012: The able-bodied athletes at the Games |publisher=BBC News |date=31 August 2012 |accessdate=31 August 2012}}</ref>

