==Broadcasting==
[[File:Trafalgar Square, Paralympics big screen.JPG|thumb|A public viewing event on the ''[[British Telecom|BT London Live]]'' stage at [[Trafalgar Square]].]]
{{main|List of 2012 Summer Paralympics broadcasters|date=October 2013}}
Broadcast rights to the 2012 Summer Paralympics were sold to local broadcasters by LOCOG, with production of the world feeds sub-contracted to [[Olympic Broadcasting Services]] (OBS). The Games saw a significant growth in media coverage for the Paralympics; LOCOG reached deals with over 36 broadcasters to televise the Games in over 100 countries. LOCOG chief [[Sebastian Coe]] stated that "beyond how the commercial value of this package has raised the bar financially for the Paralympic movement, the fantastic broadcast coverage we have agreed will help us take advantage of this opportunity to inspire disabled people of all ages to take up sport and be a catalyst for continued change in public attitudes towards disability." LOCOG reached deals with broadcasters such as [[China Central Television]], the [[Korean Broadcasting System]], [[NHK]], [[Rede Globo]] and [[SporTV]] in [[Brazil]], the TV Pool (a consortium of free-to-air broadcasters in [[Thailand]] consisting of [[Channel 3 (Thailand)|Channel 3]], [[Royal Thai Army Radio and Television Channel 5|Channel 5]], [[BBTV Channel 7]], and [[Modernine TV]]), and the [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] to air coverage.<ref name=guardian-massmarket/><ref name=nation-scramble-thisisthetvpool>{{cite web|title=Scramble to prevent blank TVs|url=http://www.nationmultimedia.com/business/Scramble-to-prevent-blank-TVs-30185620.html| work = [[The Nation]]|accessdate=26 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=telegraph-paralympictv>{{cite news|title=London 2012 Paralympics: organisers hail record broadcast deals|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9226149/London-2012-Paralympics-organisers-hail-record-broadcast-deals.html|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=4 October 2013|date=25 April 2012}}</ref><ref name=guardian-paralympictv>{{cite web|title=Paralympics TV deals break new ground as ticket rush continues|url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/aug/27/paralympics-tv-deals-ticket-rush|work=The Guardian|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref> The games were to be broadcast in the United Kingdom by [[Channel 4]], replacing long-time Paralympic broadcaster [[BBC Sport|BBC]] in a in a <U+00A3>9 million deal; the [[BBC]] still held radio rights, with coverage on [[BBC Radio 5 Live]] and [[BBC Radio 5 Live Sports Extra|5 Live Sports Extra]].<ref name=bbc-c4paralympics>{{cite news|title=Channel 4 lands 2012 Paralympics|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/olympic_games/london_2012/8448236.stm|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=4 October 2013|date=8 January 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| date = 16 August 2012 | title=BBC Paralympic Coverage Details|url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/disability-sport/19118962|publisher= [[BBC Sport]]|accessdate= 9 October 2012}}</ref><ref name="telegraph-adverts"/> The IPC [[webcast]]ed approximately 780 hours of its coverage through its [[YouTube]] channel, with four streams of coverage in [[English language|English]] and one in [[Spanish language|Spanish]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/ipc-announce-london-2012-livestream-commentators |title=IPC Announce London 2012 Livestream Commentators |publisher=[[International Paralympic Committee]] |date=16 August 2012 |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>

Channel 4's coverage of the Games was billed as the most extensive Paralympic coverage ever broadcast in the United Kingdom; it promised over 150 hours of live coverage throughout the Games on Channel 4 and sister channel [[More4]], and additional coverage online and through special channels carried by [[Freesat]], [[BSkyB|Sky]] and [[Virgin TV]] (in both standard and high definition). The broadcaster also invested around <U+00A3>600,000 towards training new on-air personalities with expertise in disability sports for the Games, many of whom were disabled themselves<U+2014>they would also be joined by ''[[Channel 4 News]]'' anchor [[Jon Snow]], and BBC Sport personality [[Clare Balding]]. Channel 4 also broadcast supplemental programming to lead towards the Games, such as Paralympic-focused documentaries, other IPC championships, and ''That Paralympic Show'', a weekly program focusing on disability sports.<ref name=dailymail-balding>{{cite news|title=INSIDE THE BOX: Balding's got Channel 4 jumping for joy as she gets on her marks to front Paralympic broadcast|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/tvshowbiz/article-2189570/Clare-Baldings-got-Channel-4-jumping-joy-gets-marks-Paralympic-broadcast.html|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=16 March 2014|location=London|first=Dan|last=Wootton|date=16 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=bbc-c4paralympics/><ref name="telegraph-adverts"/><ref name=bnow-c4paralympics>{{cite web|title=C4 opens Paralympic tender process|url=http://www.broadcastnow.co.uk/c4-opens-paralympic-tender-process/5064735.article|work=Broadcast Now|accessdate=8 February 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/info/press/news/channel-4-to-be-the-paralympic-broadcaster-in-the-uk-in-2012|title=Channel 4 to be the Paralympic Broadcaster in the UK in 2012|date=8 January 2010|publisher=[[Channel 4]]|page=3|accessdate=3 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.org/news/unprecedented-rolling-coverage-london-2012 |title=Unprecedented Rolling Coverage for London 2012 |publisher=Paralympic.org |date= |accessdate=8 July 2012}}</ref><ref name=ds-c4paralympics>{{cite web|title=Channel 4 starts Paralympic Games push|url=http://www.digitalspy.ca/media/news/a258640/channel-4-starts-paralympic-games-push.html|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref> During the Games, Comedian [[Adam Hills]] (who himself was born without a right leg, and hosted Australian coverage from [[2008 Summer Paralympics|Beijing]]) would host ''[[The Last Leg]]'', a Paralympic-themed [[late night talk show]] following the conclusion of each night's coverage.<ref>{{cite news |title=Australian comedian Adam Hills: 'I was born without a foot. Dull. Move on' |url= http://www.guardian.co.uk/theguardian/2012/aug/24/adam-hills-comedian-disability-tv-paralympics|author=Emine Saner|publisher= ''[[The Guardian]]''|date= 24 August 2012|accessdate= 19 September 2012|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |author=Metlikovec, Jane | url=http://www.news.com.au/heraldsun/story/0,21985,23888693-661,00.html | title=Comedian Adam Hills to host Paralympics |work=Herald Sun |date=19 June 2008|accessdate=19 August 2008}}</ref> Channel 4's coverage of the Games drew relatively high viewership; its coverage of the opening ceremony was seen by an average of 7.6 million viewers, a 40% share, and peaked at 11.2 million viewers<U+2014>making it one of Channel 4's most-watched programmes in network history.<ref>{{cite news|author=John Plunkett |url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/media/2012/aug/30/paralympics-opening-ceremony-8m-viewers?newsfeed=true |title=Paralympics opening ceremony attracts almost 8m viewers |publisher=The Guardian |date= 30 August 2012|accessdate=2012-08-30 |location=London}}</ref> Primetime coverage saw an average of 3.3 million viewers nightly, while viewership peaked at 4.5 million viewers during the men's T44 200m final where [[Alan Oliveira]] beat [[Oscar Pistorius]] for the gold medal.<ref name=guardian-c4ratingsoscar>{{cite web|title=Channel 4's Paralympics coverage boosted by Pistorius controversy|url=http://www.theguardian.com/media/2012/sep/03/paralympics-2012-pistorius-c4-ratings|work=The Guardian|accessdate=14 March 2014}}</ref> Its coverage of the closing ceremony peaked at 7.7 million viewers.<ref name=bbcnews-ccratings>{{cite web|title=Paralympic closing ceremony watched by 7.7m|url=http://www.bbc.com/news/entertainment-arts-19541871|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 March 2014}}</ref> 

Similarly extensive coverage was televised by [[RTVE]] in [[Spain]], with approximately 150 hours of live coverage on [[Teledeporte]] and [[TVE HD]].<ref name="rtve-para12">{{cite web|title=RTVE ofrecer<U+00E1> en Londres 2012 la mayor cobertura de unos Juegos Paral<U+00ED>mpicos| trans_title = RTVE will offer the most Paralympic Games coverage at London 2012 | language = Spanish | url=http://www.rtve.es/rtve/20120824/rtve-ofrecera-londres-2012-mayor-cobertura-unos-juegos-paralimpicos/559781.shtml|publisher= [[RTVE]]|accessdate=29 August 2012}}</ref> The [[Australian Broadcasting Corporation]] aired over 100 hours of coverage across its networks during the Paralympics, with coverage on both [[ABC1]] and [[ABC2]]. Coverage of the Games set viewership records for ABC, peaking at 1.6 million viewers on average (in comparison to 1.3 million in Beijing), while ABC2 peaked at a 4.7% viewership share, beating competing digital networks. ABC's coverage was also nominated for a [[Logie Award]] for "Moat Popular Sports Program".<ref name=apc-paralogie>{{cite web|title=ABC Paralympic coverage up for Logie award|url=http://london2012.paralympic.org.au/news/abc-paralympic-coverage-logie-award|publisher=Australian Paralympic Committee|accessdate=4 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=theaus-abc2>{{cite news|title=Paralympics a ratings winner for ABC2|url=http://www.theaustralian.com.au/media/paralympics-a-ratings-winner-for-abc/story-e6frg996-1226472161772|work=The Australian|accessdate=4 October 2013|date=12 September 2012}}</ref>

In the [[United States]], [[NBC Sports]] provided five-and-a-half hours of coverage in total, and no live coverage. Pay TV channel [[NBC Sports Network]] aired one-hour highlight shows on 4, 5, 6 and 11 September while [[NBC]] broadcast a special recapping the Games on 16 September <U+2013> a week following their conclusion. The [[United States Olympic Committee]] provided additional coverage through its own digital outlets.<ref>{{cite web| author = Press release | title=USOC announces expanded coverage for London 2012 Paralympic Games|url=http://www2.teamusa.org/US-Paralympics/Features/2012/August/14/USOC-announces-expanded-coverage-for-London-2012-Paralympic-Games.aspx|publisher= [[United States Olympic Committee]] |accessdate=14 August 2012}}</ref> Critics and American athletes expressed disappointment at NBC for its decision not to broadcast any live coverage of the Games, continuing the broadcaster's trend of providing minimal coverage for the Paralympics.<ref name=nbc-para>{{cite news|title=Paralympics 2012: NBC to only screen five-and-a-half hours retrospective coverage of Games|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9497286/Paralympics-2012-NBC-to-only-screen-five-and-a-half-hours-retrospective-coverage-of-Games.html| work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=24 August 2012|location=London|first=Gareth A|last=Davies|date=24 August 2012}}</ref> In Canada, [[The Sports Network|TSN]] (English) and [[R<U+00E9>seau des sports|RDS]] (French) produced daily hour-long highlight programs (some of which were aired by [[CTV Television]]), while tape-delayed airings of the opening ceremony were carried by [[Sportsnet One]], [[TSN2]], RDS, and [[RDS2]]. Coverage with open [[descriptive video service|described video]] was simulcast by [[AMI-tv]], a network which broadcasts programming with accommodations for those who are visually or hearing impaired, carried by all pay TV providers in Canada by law.<ref name="crtc-tacapproved">{{cite web|url=http://www.crtc.gc.ca/eng/archive/2007/db2007-246.htm|title=Broadcasting Decision CRTC 2007-246|publisher=Canadian Radio-television and Communications Commission|accessdate=27 February 2012}}</ref><ref name=amitv-para>{{cite web|title=How to Watch the London 2012 Paralympic Games|url=http://www.ctvolympics.ca/news/article/how-watch-the-london-2012-paralympic-games.html|publisher=CTVOlympics.ca|accessdate=25 August 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Follow Your Team: Canadian Paralympic Committee Announces London 2012 Paralympic Games Coverage|url=http://www.newswire.ca/en/story/1011017/follow-your-team-canadian-paralympic-committee-announces-london-2012-paralympic-games-coverage|publisher=Canadian Paralympic Committee|date=23 July 2012|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref> AMI-tv also broadcast supplemental programming, such as a daily news program from London and a documentary series focusing on Canadian athletes at the Paralympics.<ref name="ami-paralympics">{{cite web|title=Media advisory - AMI reveals reporter lineup for Paralympic Games|url=http://www.ami.ca/about/press/Pages/july-2012-2.aspx|work=Press release|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref>

== Controversies ==

=== Atos involvement ===
{{See also|Atos#Atos Healthcare|Work Capability Assessment}}
The role of IT company [[Atos]] as a technology provider and official sponsor of the Games was criticised by [[disability rights|disability-rights]] groups, due to its contract with Britain's [[Department for Work and Pensions]] to carry out [[Work Capability Assessment|work capability assessments]], which determine eligibility for [[Disability Living Allowance|disability benefits]].<ref name=guardian-oczip/> They argued that Atos's programme had lacked integrity and was intended to help cut government spending, since the assessments have resulted in many disabled workers being incorrectly judged as "fit for work" and denied benefits.<ref name=guardian-atosmp>{{cite web|title=Atos comes under attack in emotional Commons debate|url=http://www.theguardian.com/society/2013/jan/17/atos-attack-emotional-commons-debate|work=The Guardian|accessdate=5 October 2013}}</ref> Therefore, the groups considered it inappropriate for Atos to sponsor a sporting event for the disabled whilst simultaneously operating a programme that has negatively affected their lives.<ref name=guardian-atos-2/> [[UK Uncut]], a political group opposed to [[public service|public-service]] budget cuts, held a series of protests dubbed "The Atos Games" to coincide with the start of the Paralympics, culminating with demonstrations outside the London headquarters of both Atos and the Department for Work and Pensions on 31 August 2013.<ref name=guardian-atos-2>{{cite news|title=The Atos Games will showcase disabled people's anger at Paralympic sponsors|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/debate/article-2195885/The-Paralympics-celebrate-strength-disabled-people--protests-accompany-them.html| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=30 August 2012|location=London|first=Sonia|last=Poulton|date=30 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=guardian-atos1>{{cite news|title=Paralympics organisers defend sponsor Atos in face of protests|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/aug/28/atos-paraylmpic-involvement-brings-protests| work = [[The Guardian]] |accessdate=30 August 2012|location=London|first=Owen|last=Gibson|date=28 August 2012}}</ref> Speaking at the protests, comedian [[Jeremy Hardy]] said that the programme's intent to "victimise people with disabilities" was "blatant and shameless."<ref name=guardian-atos-3>{{cite news|title=Paralympic sponsor Atos hit by protests|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/society/2012/aug/31/paralympic-sponsor-atos-hit-protests?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=31 August 2012|location=London|first=Esther|last=Addley|date=31 August 2012}}</ref>

During the opening ceremony some British athletes reportedly obscured the Atos logo on their accreditation passes in protest of their involvement.<ref name=guardian-oczip/> However, an official from the [[British Paralympic Association]] denied that this had been the case.<ref name="guardian-atos-3"/> LOCOG defended Atos's involvement, stating that the company was "a critical and valued member of [the companies] delivering these Games", due to the technologies it has provided, which included information systems for managing volunteers and distributing event results.<ref name=guardian-atos1/>

=== Ticketing ===
Controversy arose about seating rules for wheelchair users, after two disabled mothers accused LOCOG of having discriminatory policies. One claimed she had been told by a LOCOG staff member that spectators in a wheelchair area at the Velodrome could only be accompanied by one adult, and children could not attend without being accompanied by another able-bodied adult, while another was told that her ability to sit in a wheelchair area with her children at [[ExCeL London]] was "not guaranteed."  A [[petition]] for improved access for disabled families, started by one of the mothers on [[Change.org]], quickly collected over 30,000 signatures. LOCOG denied having discriminatory policies, stating that disabled parents could steward their children in wheelchair seating areas at events with unreserved seats, but may not all be able to sit together at events with reserved seating.<ref name=dm-wc>{{cite news |title=Paralympics rules 'make disabled feel non-human': Fury after wheelchair-user parents are told they cannot sit with families at event |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2188996/Paralympics-rules-make-disabled-feel-non-human-Fury-wheelchair-user-parents-told-sit-families-event.html |work =[[Daily Mail]] |accessdate=18 August 2012 |location=London |first=Inderdeep |last=Bains |date=15 August 2012}}</ref><ref name=c4-assure>{{cite web |title=Locog assures disabled parents over Paralympic tickets |url=http://www.channel4.com/news/disabled-parents-successful-in-paralympic-ticket-campaign |publisher=Channel 4 |accessdate=19 August 2012}}</ref>

LOCOG faced further criticism for how it handled the sale of tickets for the wheelchair areas within venues. In May 2012 the online sale of tickets for wheelchair areas was replaced by a dedicated telephone hotline. Organisers were criticised for their use of an  [[0844]] [[Premium-rate telephone number#United Kingdom|revenue share]] number for this hotline, and for neglecting to mention on its ticketing website that calls would be charged by the minute. Former [[sports minister]] [[Gerry Sutcliffe]] viewed this as discrimination against wheelchair users, and called upon LOCOG to compensate those who had used the hotline.<ref name=bbc-bookings-discrim>{{cite news |title=Paralympics wheelchair bookings 'discriminate', MP says |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-19384473 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=29 August 2012 |date=26 August 2012}}</ref> LOCOG denied that it was receiving additional profits from the phone line, and claimed that a dedicated line was being used to allow customers to receive a service tailored to their individual accessibility needs.<ref name=telegraph-phone>{{cite news |title=Paralympics organisers accused of discriminating against wheelchair users with high-cost phone line |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9500253/Paralympics-organisers-accused-of-discriminating-against-wheelchair-users-with-high-cost-phone-line.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=28 August 2012 |location=London |date=26 August 2012}}</ref>

A minor incident occurred involving blind Member of Parliament [[David Blunkett]], who was attending the opening ceremony alongside a [[Channel 4]] director. Blunkett was denied access to his seat at Olympic Stadium because there was no room for his [[guide dog]], and had to watch the ceremony from seats in the stadium's gantry instead. However, Blunkett noted that this was an isolated incident and chose not to make an issue of it, simply advising organisers to "seek to find a solution rather than impose a preconceived notion of what is or is not possible."<ref name=telegraph-blunkett>{{cite news |title=David Blunkett turned away from stadium for Paralympics' opening ceremony because of his guide dog |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/politics/9512924/David-Blunkett-turned-away-from-stadium-for-Paralympics-opening-ceremony-because-of-his-guide-dog.html |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=11 September 2012 |location=London |first=Christopher |last=Hope |date=31 August 2012}}</ref>

=== British television coverage ===
British official broadcaster [[Channel 4]] received some criticism for its coverage of the Paralympics. Users of Twitter complained that its coverage of the opening ceremony contained too many commercial breaks, drawing comparisons to [[Olympics on NBC#2012 Opening Ceremony|similar complaints]] faced by [[NBC]] during the Olympics' opening ceremony. Complaints noted that the broadcaster had shown five ad breaks within the first hour of the ceremony, and that recently, the same channel had, ironically, broadcast a six-hour [[dance music]] special with no commercials at all. Channel 4 argued that it was broadcasting "significantly fewer" commercials than normal for primetime programming during the ceremony, and that the ad breaks were needed in order to help the channel invest in broadcasting programming such as the Paralympics. It is also to be noted that unlike [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]]'s coverage of the Olympics, which was commercial-free as it is a [[public broadcaster]] who cannot run commercial advertising, Channel 4 is an ad-supported service. Criticism was also made towards comments made by [[Jon Snow]] and [[Krishnan Guru-Murthy]] during the telecast; Snow was criticized for making comments about [[war|war-torn]] countries during the parade of nations, while Guru-Murthy received similar criticism for quipping that "looking at the ages of these athletes, which have been helpfully provided to us, they're really quite old."<ref name="telegraph-adverts">{{cite news|last=Hough |first=Andrew |url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9507747/Paralympics-2012-Channel-4-under-fire-over-opening-ceremony-adverts.html |title=Paralympics 2012: Channel 4 under fire over opening ceremony adverts |work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |date= 30 August 2012|accessdate= 30 August 2012 |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Rosie Taylor |url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2195499/Paralympics-2012-Viewers-anger-Channel-4-Opening-Ceremony-interrupted-adverts.html |title='Nice, sell cars off the back of the national anthem': Viewers' anger at Channel 4 as coverage of Opening Ceremony is interrupted by repeated advert breaks| work = [[Daily Mail]] |date= 29 August 2012|accessdate= 30 August 2012 |location=London}}</ref>

Channel 4 was also accused of showing too many studio segments during the first few days of the Games rather than live events, and for missing several notable events involving British athletes, including a swimming heat where [[Eleanor Simmonds]] set a new personal best and almost beat the world record, [[Sarah Storey]] winning her eleventh Paralympic medal, and Great Britain's opening wheelchair basketball game against Germany. Channel 4 noted that time was needed during the first few days to explain Paralympic events and the classification system to viewers, and that it was operating three additional channels' worth of live coverage throughout the Games. The broadcaster also stated that it had to make editorial decisions on which events to air during periods where a large number of events were in progress.<ref name=c4-backatcritics>{{cite news|title=Channel 4 hits back at critics after boost from Paralympics audiences|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2012/sep/01/channel-4-paralympics-audiences?newsfeed=true| work = [[The Guardian]]|accessdate=9 September 2012|location=London|first=Owen|last=Gibson|date=1 September 2012}}</ref><ref name=inde-shorts>{{cite news|title=Paralympic Shorts: It's officially the greatest Games ever|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympics/paralympic-shorts-its-officially--the-greatest-games-ever-8114025.html| work = [[The Independent]]|accessdate=9 September 2012|location=London|first=Liam|last=O'Brien|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> The amount of live coverage was also affected by [[Olympic Broadcasting Services]], who did not send cameras or provide official television coverage for sports such as cycling, the marathon, and shooting. Channel 4's [[Channel 4 News|news department]] did send its own cameramen to film the affected events for highlights, but was unable to broadcast them live.<ref name=c4-backatcritics/>

=== American television coverage===
In the United States, [[NBC Sports]] held the broadcast rights to both the Olympics and Paralympics in 2012. NBC has been frequently criticised in past years by American athletes and IPC officials for its minimal coverage of past Paralympics, and it was speculated by critics that NBC's history of inadequate coverage may have impacted [[New York City bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics|New York City's bid for the 2012 Summer Olympics and Paralympics]]. In [[2008 Summer Paralympics|2008]], it did not air any coverage while the Games were in progress (neither live or [[Broadcast delay|delayed]]), choosing to air a recap documentary on NBC in November 2008, followed by a week of highlights on [[Universal Sports]].<ref>[http://www.tvguide.com/Sports/NBC-Paralympics-Documentary-35433.aspx NBC to Air Stirring Documentary on 2008 Paralympics]" ''[[TV Guide]]''. November 7, 2008. Retrieved on November 7, 2008.</ref> While relatively larger than its Beijing coverage, NBC produced only five-and-a-half hours of specials featuring tape delayed highlights of the Games; most of them aired on pay-TV channel [[NBCSN]], while the last aired on [[NBC]] a week following the conclusion of the Games. No coverage of the opening and closing ceremonies, nor any live coverage, was provided.<ref name=nbc-para/><ref name=tele-nbc>{{cite news|title=NBC criticised Paralympics after opening ceremony blackout|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9509190/NBC-criticised-Paralympics-after-opening-ceremony-blackout.html|work = [[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=10 September 2012|location=London|date=30 August 2012}}</ref> By contrast, some broadcasters (such as the host broadcasters, and broadcasters in Australia and Spain) planned to air at least 100 hours or more of coverage from London,<ref name="tele-nbc"/><ref name=apc-paralogie/><ref name=theaus-abc2/><ref name="rtve-para12"/> and NBC itself had provided extensive coverage of the London Olympics, which ranked among the most-watched events in the history of U.S. television.<ref name=nbc-para/>

NBC's lack of coverage drew the ire of American [[disability rights]] groups and IPC president Philip Craven, who expressed his disappointment for American athletes and viewers who were unable to fully experience the games on television. Craven remarked that "some people think that North America always [leads] on everything, and on this they don't. It's about time they caught up."<ref name="tele-nbc"/> Following the closing ceremonies, Craven hinted that the IPC might exercise greater scrutiny on broadcasters at future Paralympics by stating that "if we find our [[values]] don't fit, we'll have to go somewhere else."<ref name=metro-nbc>{{cite web|title=American broadcaster NBC could lose right to show Games after criticisms|url=http://metro.co.uk/2012/09/10/american-broadcaster-nbc-could-lose-right-to-show-games-after-criticisms-569957/| work = [[Metro (British newspaper)|Metro]] |accessdate=10 September 2012}}</ref> NBC acquired the rights to the [[2014 Winter Paralympics|2014]] and [[2016 Summer Paralympics|2016]] Paralympic Games in September 2013; the broadcaster vowed to air a relatively larger amount of Paralympic coverage from [[Sochi]] and [[Rio de Janeiro]] respectively<U+2014>in particular, NBC and NBCSN are to air at least 66 hours from Rio. Craven praised NBC's decision to devote a relatively larger amount of airtime to future Paralympics, sharing his hope that U.S. audiences would be "as captivated and emotionally enthralled as the billions around the world who tuned in to London 2012 last summer."<ref name=telegraph-nbcparalympics>{{cite news|title=Paralympic Movement given huge boost as American channels NBC and NBCSN will cover next two Games|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/10330949/Paralympic-Movement-given-huge-boost-as-American-channels-NBC-and-NBCSN-will-cover-next-two-Games.html|work=The Daily Telegraph|accessdate=10 February 2014|location=London|first=Gareth A|last=Davies|date=24 September 2013}}</ref>

===Women's discus medals===

During the women's discus competition for sport classes F35/36, an error in scoring caused the wrong medals to be presented. In this combined class event, final standings were determined based on a points calculation. The calculation converted distances thrown into points, to account for the different functional impairments of the participating athletes. Due to an error in the scoring system, the gold medal in the event was originally awarded to Ukrainian athlete [[Mariia Pomazan]]. When the mistake was discovered, the recalculated points showed that Chinese athlete [[Wu Qing (athlete)|Wu Qing]] had finished first, with Pomazan in second place. A second medal ceremony was held, which Pomazan did not attend in protest. She was eventually required to return her gold medal. <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.theguardian.com/sport/2012/sep/03/paralympics-2012-gold-medal-ukrainian| publisher=The Guardian| title=Paralympic discus thrower must return gold medal, says IPC| date=3 September 2012}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/olympics/paralympic-sport/9526868/Paralympics-2012-Mariia-Pomazan-returns-discus-gold.html| publisher=The Telegraph| title=Paralympics 2012: Mariia Pomazan returns discus gold| date=6 September 2012}}</ref>

